WGBH_SUBJECT.SUBJECT: Civil rights movements United States History 20th century
March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom, Washington, D.C., 1963

WGBH_DESCRIPTION.DESCRIPTION: Al Hulsen reported from around Washington D.C. on the day of the March, and shares the personal significance of this landmark event. Mr. Hulsen was a producer and journalist from WGBH-FM in Boston in 1963. He was interviewed at Puget Sound Public Radio, KUOW 94.9 FM, in Seattle, Washington on April 29, 2011.

WGBH_SOURCE.SOURCE: Digital file supplied directly by Gary Mott in WGBH Radio

WGBH_SUBJECT.SUBJECT: March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom, Washington, D.C., 1963

WGBH_DESCRIPTION.DESCRIPTION: Caroline Isber remembers what it was like, in 1963, being one of the few women in a profession dominated by men, and the technical feat that was the Educational Radio Network’s broadcast of the March. Ms. Isber was a Radio Producer for WGBH-FM in Boston at the time of the March. She was interviewed in Washington D.C. on March 7, 2011.

WGBH_SOURCE.SOURCE: Digital file supplied directly by Gary Mott in WGBH Radio

WGBH_SUBJECT.SUBJECT: March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom, Washington, D.C., 1963

WGBH_DESCRIPTION.DESCRIPTION: Don Quayle was one of the prime movers behind the Educational Radio Network’s broadcast of the March, and says it was a grand success, but also “a traumatic experience” for him, personally. In 1963, Mr. Quayle was Manager of WGBH-FM in Boston, and one of the founders of the Educational Radio Network. He was interviewed in Bethesda, Maryland on March 8, 2011.

WGBH_SOURCE.SOURCE: Digital file supplied directly by Gary Mott in WGBH Radio

WGBH_SUBJECT.SUBJECT: March on Washington for jobs and Freedom, Washington, D.C., 1963

WGBH_DESCRIPTION.DESCRIPTION: George Geesey, the primary host of the Educational Radio Network’s coverage of the March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom, talks about the technical and creative considerations that went into the broadcast. Mr. Geesey was the Lead Engineer of the WAMU studios at American University in 1963. He was interviewed on March 7, 2011 in South Thomaston, Maine.

WGBH_SOURCE.SOURCE: Digital file supplied directly by Gary Mott in WGBH Radio

WGBH_SUBJECT.SUBJECT: March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom, Washington, D.C., 1963

WGBH_DESCRIPTION.DESCRIPTION: Rick Lee recalls the early days of network radio “experiments,” and his support of the March on Washington broadcast from WGBH-FM. Mr. Lee was interviewed at the WGBH Radio studios in Boston, Massachusetts.

WGBH_SOURCE.SOURCE: Digital file supplied directly by Gary Mott in WGBH Radio

WGBH_SUBJECT.SUBJECT: March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom, Washington, D.C., 1963

WGBH_DESCRIPTION.DESCRIPTION: Roger Penn talks about the genesis of the Educational Radio Network, and the influence that the broadcast of the March on Washington had on the creation of a national network of stations. Roger Penn was an Associate Professor at American University in 1963. He was interviewed in Falls Church, Virginia on March 7, 2011.

WGBH_SOURCE.SOURCE: Digital file supplied directly by Gary Mott in WGBH Radio

WGBH_DESCRIPTION.DESCRIPTION: Susan Stamberg reminisces about her first job as “a lowly producer” at WAMU in 1963, and the historical impact of the Educational Radio Network’s broadcast of the March. Ms. Stamberg was interviewed at NPR Headquarters on March 8, 2011.

WGBH_DESCRIPTION.DESCRIPTION: Nearly 50 years after the live radio transmission of the 1963 March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom, WGBH radio producer Gary Mott recorded the recollections of seven people involved in the broadcast. These employees of the Educational Radio Network each spoke of the difficulties and rewards of broadcasting the landmark demonstration for civil rights.
